<section xml:id="polar">
  <title>Polar Points and Regions</title>
<objectives>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <p>
        To understand the measurement of and conversions from polar coordinates
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        To practice graphing inequalities and equations in <m>r</m> and <m>\theta</m>
      </p>
    </li>
  </ul>
</objectives>
<subsection>
  <title>Polar Coordinates</title>
  <p>
    Recall that polar coordinates gives us an alternative way of representing points, curves, and regions in two dimensional space. In place of <m>(x,y)</m> we use <m>(r,\theta)</m>. Here <m>r</m> represents the distance from the origin and <m>\theta</m> is the angle made moving counterclockwise from the positive <m>x</m>-axis.
  </p>
  <activity xml:id="polar_act1">
    <task>
      <p>
        Consider the points given in the following figure. For each labeled point give the polar coordinates of the points in the form <m>(r,\theta)</m>.
      </p>
      <image width = "60%" source = "images/polar-graph.png" />
    </task>
    <task>
      <p>
        Use the equations <m>x = r \cos(\theta)</m> and <m>y = r \sin(\theta)</m> to convert the above points to <m>(x,y)</m> coordinates.
      </p>
    </task>
  </activity>
  <question>
    <p>
      For each of the three points listed below, you should</p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>Graph the point on a set of axes and label how each of the rectangular coordinates is measured.</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>Draw and label how the polar coordinates are measured for each point.</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>Compute the exact value of <m>r</m> and <m>\theta</m> for each point. Exact values include things like <m>\sqrt{3}</m>, <m>\arcsin(3/4)</m>, etc. You should simplify the trig function values of any common angles you encounter, like <m>\sin(\frac{\pi}{3})=\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}</m>.</p>
      </li>
    </ul>
    <ol>
      <li><m>(x,y)=(-1,-1)</m></li>
      <li><m>(x,y)=(2,-1)</m></li>
      <li><m>(x,y)=(-2,3)</m></li>
    </ol>
  </question>
  <question>
    <p>
      Find polar coordinates for each point given the following conditions
    </p>
    <ol>
      <li><m>(x,y)=(2,2)</m> with <m>r\geq0</m></li>
      <li><m>(x,y)=(2,2)</m> with <m>r\leq0</m></li>
      <li><m>(x,y)=(2,-2)</m> with <m>\theta\leq0</m></li>
      <li><m>(x,y)=(2,-2)</m> with <m>\theta\geq0</m></li>
    </ol>
  </question>
  <activity xml:id="polar_act2">
    <task>
      <p>
        Consider the polar regions given by the various colored areas in the following figure:
      </p>
      <image width = "100%" source = "images/polarRegion.png" />
      <p>
        For each region fill in values in the blanks
        <me>\text{___} \leq r \leq \text{___}  \qquad \text{___} \leq \theta \leq \text{___}</me>
        that represent each shaded region.
      </p>
    </task>
    <task>
      <p>
        Shade in the polar region given by the following
        <ol>
          <li><m>r \leq 2,  \qquad 0 \leq \theta \leq \frac{\pi}{3}</m></li>
          <li><m>1 \leq r \leq 2,  \qquad \frac{\pi}{4} \leq \theta \leq \frac{\pi}{2}</m></li>
          <li><m> r \leq 1, \qquad  \frac{5\pi}{4} \leq \theta \leq \frac{7\pi}{4}</m></li>
        </ol>
        Use the tool below to confirm your results.
      </p>
      <interactive xml:id="inequal_2" platform="sage" width="100%" aspect="1:1">
      <slate surface="sage">
        x,y = var('x,y')
        @interact
        def _(f1 = input_box(1, width=40, label="r > "), f2 = input_box(3, width=40, label="r &lt; "), g1 = input_box(pi/4, width=40, label="theta > "), g2=input_box(3*pi/4, width=40, label="theta &lt; ")):
          a = 1
          b = -1
          if (g1 >= pi/2 and 3*pi/2 >= g1):
            a =-1
          if (g2 >= pi/2 and  3*pi/2 >= g2):
            b = 1
          plot1 = region_plot([sqrt(x^2+y^2) >= f1, f2 >= sqrt(x^2+y^2), a*y >= a*tan(g1)*x, b*y >= b*tan(g2)*x ], (x,-4,4), (y,-4,4), incol='lightblue', plot_points=1000)
          show(plot1)
      </slate>
      </interactive>
    </task>
  </activity>
  <activity>
    <p>
      The following activity will take you through how to create a graph of an equation in <m>r</m> and <m>\theta</m>.
    </p>
    <task>
      <p>
        Draw a graph of <m> y=\cos(x)</m> for at least <m> 0 \leq x \leq 2 \pi</m>.
      </p>
    </task>
    <task>
      <p>
        For each value of <m>\theta</m> listed below, compute the value of <m>r</m> corresponding to <m> r=\cos(\theta)</m>.
      </p>
      <me>
      \theta = 0, \frac{\pi}{6}, \frac{\pi}{4},\frac{\pi}{3},\frac{\pi}{2},\frac{3\pi}{4},\pi,\frac{5\pi}{4},\frac{3\pi}{2},\frac{7\pi}{4},2\pi
      </me>
    </task>
    <task>
      <p>Plot each of the eleven points you found in the previous part on the polar plane and connect them to make a plot of the graph of <m>r=\cos(\theta)</m>.</p>
    </task>
  </activity>
  <question>
    <ol>
      <li><p>Graph the equation <m>r=1+\cos(\theta)</m> in the polar plane.</p></li>
      <li><p>Graph the equation <m>r=1-\cos(\theta)</m> in the polar plane.</p></li>
      <li><p>What are the points of intersections for the graphs of <m>r=1+\cos(\theta)</m> and <m>r=1-\cos(\theta)</m></p></li>
    </ol>
</question>
 <activity>
    <task>
      <p>
        Consider the polar regions given by the various colored areas in the following figure:
      </p>
      <image width = "100%" source = "images/polarRegion2.png" />
      <p>
        For each region fill in values in the blanks
        <me>\text{___} \leq r \leq \text{___}  \qquad \text{___} \leq \theta \leq \text{___}</me>
        that represent each shaded region.
      </p>
    </task>
  </activity>
</subsection>
